article.description:
Kobe Bryant made it six straight games of 35
points or more by scoring 42 despite sitting out the fourth quarter
Tuesday night as the Los Angeles Lakers extended their winning
streak to a season-high six by beating Denver 121-93.
article.headline: Bryant only needs three quarters to score 42 points
article.linkText: Bryant lights up Nuggets for 42 points in Lakers' win
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kobe Bryant keeps scoring, and the Los Angeles Lakers keep winning.
Bryant

Bryant made it six straight games of 35 points or more by scoring 42 despite sitting out the entire fourth quarter Tuesday night as the Lakers extended their winning streak to a season-high six by beating the Denver Nuggets 121-93. "He's my choice for the MVP right now,'' teammate Shaquille O'Neal said. "He's playing at a very high level, shooting the ball well and everybody's following his lead. "Sometimes the one does it, sometimes the two does it. Right now the one's doing it and I'm chilling out. It's all good.'' O'Neal had 20 points, eight rebounds, five assists and three blocked shots while also sitting out the fourth quarter. Bryant has scored 243 points (40.5 average) during the winning streak. He played 31 minutes against the Nuggets, shooting 12-of-20 and making 17 of 21 free throws. The totals could have been higher, but with the Lakers leading 100-66 after three quarters, Bryant wasn't needed after that. Bryant acknowledged he's probably never had a more productive period in terms of scoring, but said he's had stretches where he's played better all-around basketball. "I just feel I'm in a very good rhythm right now,'' he said. "It's coming pretty easy. I've been able to help our team win some games and that's been the best part. "The past six games here, we're playing perhaps the best basketball in the league. We're the champions until somebody takes it away from us.'' Bryant has scored 40 or more points 10 times this season. The last Laker to accomplish such a feat was Hall of Famer Jerry West, who scored 40 or more 13 times during the 1969-70 season. Lakers coach Phil Jackson said the way Bryant is playing is comparable to the way Michael Jordan played when Jackson coached the Chicago Bulls to six championships in the 1990s. "But it's a totally different style of attack,'' Jackson said. "Kobe does a lot of things with the ball and Michael did a lot of things off the ball. Both of them have the ability where everything seems to go to them. "I think these guys really recognize the fact that Kobe is in the zone right now and they're making the most of it.'' Samaki Walker had 14 points and Derek Fisher, Kareem Rush and Devean George added 10 each as the Lakers (25-23) moved a season-high two games over .500. The three-time defending champions have won 14 of 18 games to move within a half-game of Houston in the race for the final Western Conference playoff berth. Vincent Yarbrough and Juwan Howard led the Nuggets (12-38) with 18 points each and Chris Whitney added 14 points and five assists. Yarbrough equaled his career high before leaving with an injured right leg midway through the fourth quarter. He left the court under his own power, and coach Jeff Bzdelik said after the game that Yarbrough was fine. "It's quite obvious the Lakers have absolutely no fear of us whatsoever,'' Bzdelik said. "The Lakers are on a roll and will be hard to deal with for everyone. "I told our players if they want autographs, get them before the game." Playing just his second game of the season, Denver's Marcus Camby had two points, four rebounds, two assists and two blocked shots in 16 minutes. He missed the first 38 games recovering from hip surgery and the last 10 after spraining his right ankle. The Lakers and Nuggets meet again Wednesday night in Denver, and Camby said he hopes to play. "I didn't shoot particularly well, so I want to redeem myself,'' he said. "I just want to compete, get back in the flow and let things fall where they may.'' Bryant scored 23 points as the Lakers took a 58-45 halftime lead. The Nuggets weren't closer than 11 points in the second half. Baskets by Walker, Bryant and O'Neal made it 72-54 with seven minutes left in the third quarter. Then, with the Staples Center crowd of 18,848 in a frenzy, Bryant scored 11 points during a 13-2 run he capped with a 3-pointer to make it 96-64 with 51 seconds left in the period. Game notes
The Lakers have won 20 of the last 25 games between the teams. ... Jackson said he hadn't decided whether he would punish O'Neal for missing practice Monday since the two hadn't spoken about it. "I'm not concerned about it,'' Jackson said. "I wasn't planning on practicing him anyway.'' O'Neal phoned the team to say he wouldn't be at practice because he was taking his pregnant wife to the doctor. He played in Sunday night's All-Star game in Atlanta. ... The Nuggets have lost 10 straight road games and have a 3-22 road record. ... The game marked the beginning of a stretch in which the Lakers play 11 of 14 games at home. ... Camby made only one of eight shots -- a baseline jumper in the second quarter. He didn't play in the fourth period. ... The Lakers made their first 16 foul shots before Bryant missed a pair late in the second quarter. ... Bryant's 21 attempts from the foul line equaled an NBA season-high.
